A class contains the following two method headers:

```java
public int getValue(int n)
public double getValue(int n)
```

Why will this code **not** compile?

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
public static void doubleIt(int x) {
    x = x * 2;
}

public static void main(String[] args) {
    int num = 5;
    doubleIt(num);
    System.out.println(num);
}
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
public static int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

public static int add(int a, int b, int c) {
    return add(a, b) + c;
}

public static void main(String[] args) {
    System.out.println(add(2, 3, 4));
}
```

Consider the following method:

```java
public static int mystery(int n) {
    int result = 0;
    while (n > 0) {
        result += n % 10;
        n /= 10;
    }
    return result;
}
```

What value does `mystery(253)` return?

A class named `Calculator` is defined in a separate file and contains the following method:

```java
public static double average(int a, int b) {
    return (a + b) / 2.0;
}
```

Which of the following correctly calls this method and stores the result?

In the following code, what is the correct term for the value `5` in the call `square(5)`?

```java
public static int square(int n) {
    return n * n;
}

int result = square(5);
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
public static String describe(int n) {
    if (n > 0) {
        return "positive";
    }
    return "non-positive";
}

public static String describe(double n) {
    return "decimal";
}

public static void main(String[] args) {
    System.out.println(describe(3));
    System.out.println(describe(3.0));
    System.out.println(describe(-1));
}
```

Consider the following method:

```java
public static int multiply(int a, int b) {
    return a * b;
}
```

Which of the following calls will cause a **compile-time error**?

Consider the following code:

```java
public static void addFive(int n)
{
    n = n + 5;
}

public static void main(String[] args)
{
    int score = 10;
    addFive(score);
    System.out.println(score);
}
```

What is printed when this code is executed?

A programmer writes the following method:

```java
public static void doubleValue(int n)
{
    return n * 2;
}
```

Which of the following best describes the problem with this code?

Consider the following code:

```java
public static int swap(int a, int b)
{
    int temp = a;
    a = b;
    b = temp;
    return a + b;
}

public static void main(String[] args)
{
    int x = 4;
    int y = 9;
    int z = swap(x, y);
    System.out.println(x + " " + y + " " + z);
}
```

Determine the values of `x`, `y`, and `z` after this code executes.

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
public static void addFive(int n) {
    n += 5;
}

public static void main(String[] args) {
    int x = 10;
    addFive(x);
    System.out.println(x);
}
```

Determine the output of the following code:

```java
public static String build(String first, String second) {
    return second + first;
}

public static void main(String[] args) {
    System.out.println(build("bye", "good"));
}
```

Consider the following method headers in the same class.

```java
public static int calc(int a, double b)
public static int calc(double a, int b)
public static String calc(String a, int b)
```

Which of the following method calls will cause a compiler error?

A class already contains the following method.

```java
public static int combine(int x, int y)
{
    return x + y;
}
```

Which of the following methods could be added to the same class without causing a compiler error?

options.text:
```java
public static double combine(int x, int y)
{
    return x + y + 0.5;
}
```

```java
public static int combine(int y, int x)
{
    return x + y;
}
```

```java
public static int combine(double x, int y)
{
    return (int) x + y;
}
```

```java
public static int combine(int x, int y)
{
    return x * y;
}
```
